definition.value: The residue in a peptide that has a free carboxyl group, or at least does not acylate another amino-acid residue, is called C-terminal.
The residue in a peptide that has an amino group that is free, or at least not acylated by another amino-acid residue, is called N-terminal.
Any C-terminal amino-acid residue derived from an alpha-amino-acid.
Any C-terminal alpha-amino-acid residue derived from a proteinogenic amino acid.
A polypeptide compound composed of ten natural and non-natural amino acid resiudes in a linear sequence.

A cluster is a number of metal centres grouped close together which can have direct metal bonding interactions or interactions through a bridging ligand, but are not necessarily held together by these interactions.
Any aldonic acid formed by oxidising the aldehyde group of an aldohexose to a carboxylic acid group.
A hexonic acid derivative that is formally obtained from fuconic acid.
An aldonate obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy group of any pentonic acid.
